         <abstract>
            <p>Written frankly for money, Charles Dickens' biography of the English stage-clown, Joseph Grimaldi, has generally been dismissed as hackwork. Dickens's Memoirs of Joseph Grimaldi, though, discloses persistent Victorian attitudes toward performers and performing, and anticipates in uncanny ways the biographical commentary that surrounds Dickens's own career as a performer.</p>
         </abstract>
